arising from the medial surface of the lateral pterygoid plate and posterior surface of the

maxilla. Follow its fibres inferiorly and posteriorly to their attachment to the medial surface of the mandible near the angle. 
The medial pterygoid muscles on both sides act together in elevation and protrusion of the mandible. 
One medial pterygoid acting alone will play a role in helping to rotate the mandible to the opposite side, for example when grinding your teeth.
